== History == {{ill|Ikeda Noriyuki|ja|池田章政|12=draft}}, the lord of {{ill|Okayama Domain|ja|岡山藩|12=draft}}, held a spirit summoning festival for 34 war dead, including {{ill|Suzume Hachiro Tokioki|ja|雀部八郎時宜|12=draft}} from the {{ill|Boshin War|ja|戊辰戦争|12=draft}}'s {{ill|Battle of Aizu|ja|奥羽戦争|12=draft}}, on April 3, {{ill|1869|ja|1869th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|12=draft}} 2), at the current site of {{ill|Korakuen|ja|後楽園|12=draft}} park's back bamboo field. In June of the same year, a shrine and stone monument were built on an 180 tsubo site in Kamida Village, Joto District, to worship the war dead from the Aizu and {{ill|Hakodate War|ja|函館戦争|12=draft}}.
On March 17, [[:en:1874|1874]] (Meiji 7), it became an official government shrine and was named Okayama Shokonsha. In [[:en:1922|1922]] (Taisho 4), it was relocated to its current location, and the shrine buildings were completed on April 26. On April 1, {{ill|1939|ja|1939th year|12=draft}} (Showa 14), it was designated by the Minister of Home Affairs and renamed Okayama Prefecture Gokoku Shrine. For a period after the war, it was called Sōzan Shrine due to the Allied occupation policies, but it reverted to its current name in {{ill|1952|ja|1952nd year |lt=1955|12=draft}} (Showa 27). Various renovations have been carried out since the war.
== Access == * {{ill|Okayama Prefectural Route 28 Okayama Ushimado Line|ja|岡山県道28号岡山牛窓線|12=draft}} * Take the {{ill|Ryobi Bus|ja|両備ホールディングス|12=draft}} bound for {{ill|Saidaiji Bus Center|ja|西大寺バスセンター|12=draft}} and get off at "Gokoku Shrine" bus stop.
