On March 17, [[:en:1874|1874]] (Meiji 7), it became an official government shrine and was named Okayama Shokonsha. In [[:en:1922|1922]] (Taisho 4), it was relocated to its current location, and the shrine buildings were completed on April 26. On April 1, {{ill|1939|ja|1939th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Showa 14), it was designated by the Minister of Home Affairs and renamed Okayama Prefecture Gokoku Shrine. For a period after the war, it was called Sōzan Shrine due to the Allied occupation policies, but it reverted to its current name in {{ill|1952|ja|1952nd year |lt=1955|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Showa 27). Various renovations have been carried out since the war.

== Access ==
* {{ill|Okayama Prefectural Route 28 Okayama Ushimado Line|ja|岡山県道28号岡山牛窓線|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* Take the {{ill|Ryobi Bus|ja|両備ホールディングス|qq=draft|qq=draft}} bound for {{ill|Saidaiji Bus Center|ja|西大寺バスセンター|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and get off at "Gokoku Shrine" bus stop.

