'''Okayama Prefecture Gokoku Shrine''' (岡山護国神社) is a [[:en:Gokoku shrines|Gokoku Shrine]] located in Okuichi, [[:en:Naka-ku, Okayama|Naka-ku]], [[:en:Okayama|Okayama]], [[:en:Okayama Prefecture|Okayama Prefecture]]. The former [[Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]] classification was a Designated Gokoku Shrine by the Minister of Home Affairs, and it became a [[:en:Beppyo shrine|Beppyo Shrine]] after the war.
[[Ja:岡山護国神社]]
The shrine grounds feature numerous memorial monuments to the war dead, including memorials for those interned in Siberia and a memorial for Navy Vice Admiral {{ill|Matome Ugaki|ja|宇垣纒|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matome Ugaki|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 宇垣纏}} and the seventeen warriors of Kikusui.

== History ==
{{ill|Ikeda Noriyuki|ja|池田章政|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikeda Noriyuki|qq=}}, the lord of [[:en:Okayama Domain|Okayama Domain]], held a spirit summoning festival for 34 war dead, including {{ill|Suzume Hachiro Tokioki|ja|雀部八郎時宜|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suzume Hachiro Tokioki|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} from the [[:en:Boshin War|Boshin War]]'s {{ill|Battle of Aizu|ja|奥羽戦争|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Aizu|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 戊辰戦争}}, on April 3, [[:en:1869|1869]] ([[:en:Meiji era|Meiji era]] 2), at the current site of [[:en:Kōraku-en|Korakuen]] park's back bamboo field. In June of the same year, a shrine and stone monument were built on an 180 tsubo site in Kamida Village, Joto District, to worship the war dead from the Aizu and {{ill|Hakodate War|ja|函館戦争|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hakodate War|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 箱館戦争}}.

On March 17, [[:en:1874|1874]] (Meiji 7), it became an official government shrine and was named Okayama Shokonsha. In [[:en:1922|1922]] (Taisho 4), it was relocated to its current location, and the shrine buildings were completed on April 26. On April 1, [[:en:1939|1939]] (Showa 14), it was designated by the Minister of Home Affairs and renamed Okayama Prefecture Gokoku Shrine. For a period after the war, it was called Sōzan Shrine due to the Allied occupation policies, but it reverted to its current name in [[:en:1952|1955]] (Showa 27). Various renovations have been carried out since the war.

== Access ==
* {{ill|Okayama Prefectural Route 28 Okayama Ushimado Line|ja|岡山県道28号岡山牛窓線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okayama Prefectural Route 28 Okayama Ushimado Line|qq=}}
* Take the [[:en:Ryobi Holdings|Ryobi Bus]] bound for {{ill|Saidaiji Bus Center|ja|西大寺バスセンター|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saidaiji Bus Center|qq=}} and get off at "Gokoku Shrine" bus stop.

